<h1>Middleware</h1>

<p>
    Custom middleware lives anywhere in your project. Mark a class with
    <code>[Middleware]</code> and Nxt's source generator registers it in the pipeline.
</p>

<h2>Example: a request logger</h2>
<pre><code>using Nxt;

namespace SampleApp.Middleware;

[Middleware(order: 10)]
public class RequestLogger(ILogger&lt;RequestLogger&gt; logger)
&#123;
    public async Task InvokeAsync(HttpContext ctx, RequestDelegate next)
    &#123;
        var sw = System.Diagnostics.Stopwatch.StartNew();
        await next(ctx);
        logger.LogInformation("&#123;Method&#125; &#123;Path&#125; → &#123;Status&#125; in &#123;Ms&#125;ms",
            ctx.Request.Method, ctx.Request.Path,
            ctx.Response.StatusCode, sw.ElapsedMilliseconds);
    &#125;
&#125;</code></pre>

<h2>Rules</h2>
<ul>
    <li>The class must define
        <code>InvokeAsync(HttpContext, RequestDelegate)</code> — matches the ASP.NET Core
        convention.</li>
    <li>Constructor injection works — the class is resolved from the request scope.</li>
    <li><code>order</code> controls relative ordering — lower runs earlier in the pipeline.
        Default is <code>100</code>.</li>
    <li>Middleware runs <em>after</em> Nxt's built-in pieces
        (<code>UseAntiforgery</code>, etc.) and <em>before</em> endpoint execution.</li>
</ul>

<h2>When NOT to use this</h2>
<p>
    For middleware that needs precise positioning (<code>UseAuthentication</code>,
    <code>UseSession</code>, <code>UseForwardedHeaders</code>), use
    <code>NxtHostOptions.ConfigureMiddleware</code> in <code>Program.cs</code> — it slots
    your middleware between <code>UseRouting</code> and the endpoint mappings:
</p>

<pre><code>opts.ConfigureMiddleware = app =&gt;
&#123;
    app.UseAuthentication();
    app.UseAuthorization();
&#125;;</code></pre>
